@probahilliby I've come to realise that relying on news can be a pitfall. I didn't recall seeing the words "section 30" in the articles that I read, so I didn't think to dig deeper.

I think my previous analysis still stands (https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1473028) but the phrasing of the question seems unclear to me as to what exactly counts as an official request rather than an informal request, so I am just hedging for today on the off chance that Sturgeon's announcement of a letter resolves the question.

Asking for a referendum doesn't mean there will be one. In fact, it doesn't even mean that one is desired (at least not in the timeframe of asking). It might be in the interest of the independence movement to have another request rejected. However, with that said, it is a risk to ask for one if you believe you won't succeed as you can't really row back on it once the wheels are in motion.

My sense, is at this point, Scottish opinion is too closely matched to really justify pushing for a referendum that could so easily fail. As such, the Scottish government is much more likely to hold off.

Reshift as I am unsure how formal the request has to be, despite being "official." Something can be official but still quite rudimentary in progress.

The SNP and Greens will want to focus for the next 6 months on settling into their new jobs and getting policies passed, and letting the coronavirus pandemic pass. They have agreed to try to hold another referendum by the end of 2023. They will need to allow at least a year to negotiate with the Westminster government and/or drag it through the courts, and to allow 3 months prior to a referendum. They will want the public to either have had the referendum in late 2023, or have been disappointed by Westminster around that time, as that will give both parties an axe to grind during the May 2024 general election campaign. And the longer the Tories stay in power, the better for the chance of a vote for independence. All of these factors push a referendum date to late 2023, which means the section 30 request has go in in late 2022 or early 2023. Given uncertainty over coronavirus returning next winter, early 2023 is more likely.

The UK is busy dealing with Ireland and the hard border, leaving Scottish people with unanswered contention points. These contentions will boil over by summer and will lead to calls for independence. This external pressure will cause the Scottish government to request discussions and agreements on Section 30.

Indyref 2 in this parliament is a promise the SNP are nearly certain to keep - not only is it a driving factor for some of their base, it's also ideologically very important to most leading figures in the party. However, timing is important. There's four and a half years left in this parliament, and in the abstract it's not obvious why 2022 - likely still very much dominated by the pandemic - would be the 'right time' to start the timer on Indyref 2. There has been discussion in the press about Sturgeon stepping down - it all seems to be speculation rather than sourced, so I wouldn't put any serious weight on it, but if there's any chance of this then it would push the referendum further into the future. That leads me to think that no announcement in 2022 is a possibility.
Incumbent will not stay past 2022 so successor may be more capable of formal request, but knowing this will be declined. Unclear who would be successor.
Timing is everything on this issue for Scotland.

In its pre-election manifesto, the SNP pledged to hold a new Scottish independence referendum “after the COVID crisis is over.” This rules out any date before January 2022, as January 2022 is right in the middle of winter, when Covid cases should be on an upswing. Prime Minister Johnson has been quoted as stating that the idea of an independence referendum is irresponsible and reckless, and ultimately the power to grant Scotland an independence referendum rests in London, not Edinburg. A second independence referendum is opposed by British Party leaders, and even Scottish party leaders, including Scottish Conservative leaders, Scottish Labour leaders, and Scottish Liberal Democrat leaders.
NS latest position is a referendum before the end of 2023, but after "data-driven evidence" indicate the pandemic is under control.

One issue is that the COP26 climate conference (International) is to be held in Glasgow in October and she has just gone into coalition (ish) with the Greens to gain a majority for Independence MSP’s in Hollyrood. She has the Greens on her left, 100,000 potential jobs loss on her right and 50/50% split on voter need for a referendum. Her best hope is for Boris to slump in the UK polls over his tax increases to cover health care. Nicola Sturgeon has so far stuck to saying that they intend to move for independence within the first half of the Scottish parliamentary term i.e., before the end of 2023. A section 30 request is unlikely to happen while dealing with the pandemic and recovery is the immediate priority - for both practical and political reasons. Support for an independent Scotland will increase if the scottish government does a good job - one might assume they are counting on this - which requires enough time to pass for people to get that impression.

I am still sceptic about a new referendum if it is 50/50. https://www.politico.eu/europe-poll-of-polls/united-kingdom/ On the other side, if we consider that Sturgeon want a new referendum, her government had to initiate the processus a lot of time before. The question is about the beginning of the processus, not the referendum itself. https://news.sky.com/story/scottish-government-to-restart-work-on-detailed-prospectus-for-independence-nicola-sturgeon-says-12401446

Looking at history, there were two requests for discussions on or agreement to a section 30 order. One was in either 2011 or 2012 (too tired to check) and the other in 2017. These were 1-2 years after Scottish Parliament elections. The latest election took place on 6 May 2021, so it looks like there's a good chance of a section 30 request or mandate in the specified timeframe.

Nicola Sturgeon has stated that she is determined to hold an independence referendum during he present parliament. The next election will be held on or before May 2025. The SNP’s limited coalition has been formed to give the SNP a majority in Holyrood which has also allowed to Green MSPs into government. This might create issues in the future given the comments made by the Spectator magazine as describing the Scottish Greens as ‘ unhinged, eccentric and outside the mainstream’. (to say the least). Sturgeon in her election declarations stated that she wanted a referendum in the the first half of her Parliamentary term which would suggest some time in 2023. Assuming at least a 12-month period to prepare such a large-scale referendum, the discussions (if allowed) would have to be completed by the beginning of 2023, which suggest Sturgeon’s program to commence talks in 2022. The UK Government Scottish Secretary, Alister Jack has suggested that could be agreement to an independence referendum if sustained opinion polling shows a 60% support for holding it is achieved. This has been dismissed by Sturgeon probably due to the current +/- 44% support. She has agreed that the Covid pandemic must be fought through prior to her pushing for the UK Government to accede to negotiations (doubtful at this stage) which precludes 2021, then a formal request to commence the talks would on her plan begin in 2022. Given her up and coming legal issues with claims of fraudulent activities in the SNP financial accounts, the out-of-control drug deaths in Scotland and now the precarious nature of her Green based majority, Sturgeon would need the distraction of an IndyRef2 as soon as possible.
Coalition with greens makes early requests possible but after elections is more likely

There is still not according to the polls a majority in Scotland for an independence vote, with the ‘NO’ vote leading ‘YES’ by 3% and 9% not sure. The UK government will therefore not be minded to open discussions concerning Article 30 order. The SNP and Scottish Greens have fundamental differences in policies but a limited coalition has added 7 seats to the SNP’s 64, that has now provided a majority in Parliament to request independence discussions with the UK government. The SNP’s raison d’etre with Sturgeon at its head is to achieve Independence for Scotland, as is the Greens. It is conceivable that a Supreme Court opinion, to circumvent an article 30 order, will find against the Scottish Parliament as it would be a political issue rather than a point of law. The UK government can disassociate itself from this by letting a private citizen in Scotland, take the lead and challenge the bill in the Court of Session and deny Sturgeon any headlines. Problems are mounting for Sturgeon in that the SNP auditors ‘have included an unprecedented statement about fraud in the party’s new accounts as police investigate potential criminality around the Indyref2 fundraising’. This will hurt both Sturgeon and her husband, Peter Murrell who is the chief executive of SNP. This has been admitted and stated that an equivalent sum will be added to the funds. This does suggest irregularities. Scotland has more drug deaths than any other country in Europe (3 times than that of England and Wales. Given the demands from her party to hold a referendum and pressure from the opposition over the out-of-control drug deaths together with potential fraud issues, Sturgeon requires a distraction and her majority in the Scottish Parliament (with the Greens) will provide one in the form of a request for Article 30 discussions to commence. Another indication is that the SNP have increased the number of press officers (spin doctors) by 42% over the last years that suggests a ramping up of a PR program with one aim in mind – IndyRef2. I suggest she therefore proceed sooner rather than later before she overwhelmed by problems.

it is not that they want to secede, but want to use it as a negotiation issue. But given Covid and the return of troops and other national issues, it is unlikely Scotland will force London for immediate concessions for them.
Sturgeon spoke of legislation possible early next year First focus needs to be covid. When vaccinations are at full coverage and major infections drop away then should expect some progress

Based on the May election, SNP believes they have a mandate to hold another referendum. Current polling suggests 47% support a referendum in the next year, although the "No" vote seems to be ahead by 3%. The UK has specified they'd like to see support for a referendum at 60% before granting another referendum vote. But it UK granting section 30 and Scotland beginning discussions are two different things.
